Basic instructions for getting going with TGLF-EP+Alpha

ENVIRONMENT SETUP
-------------------

Set environment variables in your login script for TGLFEP and Alpha directories.
There are two "public" Perlmutter installs:

For AToM legacy team members:

/global/common/software/atom/gacode_add_TGLFEP

For DIII-D collaborators:

/global/cfs/cdirs/m3739/gacode_add_d3d

Choose the appropriate root directory for yourself above, referred to below as "$ROOT".
Both should be current with all updates.

for c-shell:

 setenv TGLFEP_DIR $ROOT/TGLF-EP
 setenv ALPHA_DIR $ROOT/Alpha

for bash

 export $TGLFEP_DIR='$ROOT/TGLF-EP'
 export $ALPHA_DIR='$ROOT/Alpha'

PREPARING RUN DIRECTORY
---------------------------------------------

Copy all template files to run directory.

Add the input.gacode for your case to your run directory.
 * The EP species (whetehr one or two) and kinetically-treated species MUST have continuous
   indices in input.gacode, with non-kinetic impurities following. Please reorder input.gacode to
   meet this condition.
 * Input files here assume thermal deuterium at index 1 and deuterium beam at index 2.
 * For other configurations (e.g. running carbon kinetically), adjust the following variables appropriately:
   - In input.TGLFEP:
     * N_ION (total kinetic ions including EP(s))
     * IS_EP (index for EP species on this TGLFEP run)
   - In Alpha_input, lines with following labels:
     * # First species index in input.gacode
     * # Main ion mass in AMU
     * # Main ion charge in e
     * # Secondary thermal ion mass in AMU
     * # Secondary thermal charge in e
     * # Fraction of primary thermal ion
     * Note: Only two main thermal ions are allowed currently in Alpha.
             The above paramters MUST be set manually; 
               consistancy with input.gacode is not yet automatic
Other parameters a typical user might want to adjust in input.TGLFEP
* SCAN_N: Controls how many radial domain points are sampled.
* ROTATIONAL_SUPPRESSION_FLAG: 0 no ExB quech of AEs
                               1 ExB quench from Bass and Waltz, PoP 2017

SETTING UP RUN
-----------------------------------------------

The number of cores per radial gridpoint must divide evenly in 256 (up to 256).
Set values in batch_TGLFEP.sl appropriately (Alpha is uniprocess, so need to touch batch_Alpha.sl):
#SBATCH --nodes=10        (number of need nodes = cores/128)
#SBATCH --time=3:00:00    (run time requested, 3 hrs should be plenty for 2 kinetic species)
#SBATCH -J adaptive       (name of run on slurm queue)

srun -n 1280 $TGLFEP_DIR/TGLFEP_driver
       |____|
         |_________ Number of cores

EXECUTE THE RUN
-----------------------------------------------

At command line just submit each batch file

TGLFEP:

sbatch batch_TGLFEP.sl

Outputs:

out.scalefactor.*   (summary of TGLFEP searching algorithm)
out.wavefunction.*  (wavefunctions)
alpha_dndr_crit.input    (critical gradient in density units)
alpha_dpdr_crit.input    (critical gradient in pressure units)
run.err.TGLFEP           (standard error)
run.out.TGLFEP           (standard output)

If you have critical gradients from TGLFEP, you can run Alpha (uniprocess):

sbatch batch_Alpha.sl

Outputs (1 EP species):

Alpha_dndr_crit_composite.out
Alpha_dpdr_crit_composite.out
Alpha.out      (basic run summary)
Alpha_transport.out    (all the important transport files)
D_alpha_ITER.out      (EP diffusion coefficient profile in ITER-standard units for TRANSP/NUBEAM)
D_alpha.out           (EP diffusion coefficient profile in usual units)
out.Alpha.sigma_v_vs_rho  (DT fusion cross section vs radius, meaningless for non DT plasma)
run.err.Alpha       (standard error)
run.out.Alpha       (standard output)
